erbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]},{"name":"Heather","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller on the heath’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>hethe</i>; compare   Heath  . The name may also be habitational name from Heather (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>hǣthor</i> ‘heathland’ (<i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + the noun suffix <i>-or</i>) or <i>hǣddre</i> ‘heather’. This surname is widespread in southern England, and also established in Ireland."]},{"name":"Health","meanings":["(1997: 105;2010: NA)","Altered form of English and Scottish   Heath  .","English and Scottish: perhaps a nickname from the vocabulary word <i>health</i>. — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is 105."]},{"name":"Hoad","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, from Middle English <i>hoth</i> ‘heath’ (Old English <i>hāth</i>, a byform of Old English <i>hǣth</i>), or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Hoath in Kent. This form was restricted in the Middle Ages to southeastern England, and the surname is still largely confined to Kent, Surrey, and Sussex. Compare   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]}]},{"name":"N.N.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"N.N. Heath was born from 1465 to 1519. She had at least 1 son with Robert Heath."},"et":{"between 1465 and 1519 –":"1465 kuni 1519–Surnud","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1525–1593":"1525–1593","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1525":"1525","between 1465 and 1519 ":"1465 kuni 1519","1465":"1465","1575":"1575","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","England":"England"},"fi":{"between 1465 and 1519 –":"vuodesta 1465 vuoteen 1519–Kuollut","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1525–1593":"1525–1593","1465–Female":"1465–Kuollut","1525":"1525","between 1465 and 1519 ":"vuodesta 1465 vuoteen 1519","1465":"1465","1575":"1575","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","England":"England"},"fr":{"between 1465 and 1519 –":"du 1465 au 1519–Décédée","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1525–1593":"1525–1593","1465–Female":"1465–Décédée","1525":"1525","between 1465 and 1519 ":"du 1465 au 1519","1465":"1465","1575":"1575","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"N.N. Heath est née du 1465 au 1519. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Robert Heath."},"de":{"between 1465 and 1519 –":"von 1465 bis 1519–Verstorben","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1525–1593":"1525–1593","1465–Female":"1465–Verstorben","1525":"1525","between 1465 and 1519 ":"von 1465 bis 1519","1465":"1465","1575":"1575","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","England":"England","lifeSummary":"N.N. Heath wurde von 1465 bis 1519 geboren. Sie hatte mit Robert Heath mindestens 1